text: While this does look like it has some amazing action, which seems to have all been shown in this trailer, they really seem to be throwing out all notion of credibility far as dynamics go. If a ship as large as this alien one came anywhere near earth, it would  radically alter not only the spin, but the velocity, and trajectory of earths orbit to the point of catastrophic no return. In reality the subsequent alien air and ground forces in this kind of scenario would not serve the aliens at all. They would only have to, either, bombard us to hell from outside the orbit of the moon, (which they'd be more than capable of), or just come near enough to earth to alter it and the moons orbit, then fly away and await our quick, and inevitable demise. While I will watch it and most likely enjoy it, it's sad they'd toss out the reality of physics, as well as, any notion of alien strategy or capability, for nothing but an action orgy. There is, absolutely, no sound reason these aliens would come in with fists flying in a blind frenzy of hate and revenge, and destruction, tossing out all reason, when they would not even have to so much as scuff a boot, or break a nail to get what they want from us. Ridiculous.

text: You know, I would have really, honestly, LOVED it, if for once, Mankind was MUCH more badass than depicted in movies like this. Don't get me wrong, Idependence Day will be hysterically epic. But, at the extent of a large fraction of the world's population... Again. And THEN they killed Will Smith's character off, which is another, "Ew". Just saying, 20 years with the particular technology that this alien race had, which is RIDICULOUSLY advanced and probably an entire another millennia ahead of ours (Or 4); it should have yielded far better gifts to mankind. What I just saw, resembled today's world in, MAYBE, another 80 years; If not a single century. Today's world IF everything changed for the better, and I mean that from an economic aspect. But, eh, I am done ranting. I don't know, maybe I am just wanting people to have more faith in mankind, regardless of what we are seeing today. Naive? I would not say so. Optimist?  Maybe. Passionate about mankind doing great things and THE RIGHT things? Definitely.~‚ô°

Sure, models and practical effects are cool too, but sometimes you just need CGI, and it's not a bad thing to use it.  Because at this point, it looks real enough to pass.  Back in the days of say, The Matrix and Revenge of the Sith, CGI wasn't ready to do people and such.  But.. Now it is.  And how about Fury Road?  Lots of CGI in that.  Not the cars, no, because the point of the Mad Max movies is making crazy cars.  But the landscapes?  Basically 90% CGI.  Similarly, the point of Independence Day movies is destroying all the things, so.. who cares if they're CGI things or not?

text: The irony is in this film's title "Independence Day", yet like most of the mainstream media/"entertainment" industry, it is part of the mental control mechanism which now strives to completely erode independence and sovereignty (on both a national & individual level). What comes off as "harmless fiction", can get us to more easily accept certain changes, narratives, and policies that are currently here, being introduced to us, and coming down the line. Just like the "War on Terror" managed to traumatize people into giving away their freedoms to psychopathic "authorities", so to will any major future incident on the pretense of establishing a one world government. Politicians - the same ones who call for a "one world government", or "new world order" - have mused for years how "united" the world would be if some otherworldly threat came down to scare people enough to "put aside their differences". Only it won't be "aliens", it will be tyrants putting on some dramatic show to fool us into supporting their political agendas, which they never would be able to achieve otherwise.  When one remembers how many false flag attacks those in power have planned & initiated throughout history, how their "solutions" always revolve around worship of the collective, and how they have used the media tool to dupe us into falling for it,  it isn't too hard to imagine how such a scenario might take place when it comes to so-called "aliens".

Overall the story line seems ok.  I was sad to learn that WIll Smith isn't in the movie, since he did such an awesome job in the original.  Plus I liked his work in his many other sci-fi thrillers.  Unfortunately, after watching this trailer, I have a feeling resurgence will be lucky if it's half as good as the original.  Even the clips of the actors that were in the original were pretty lame, and has me thinking there may be an issue with the screenwriting or directing.  I will still go see the movie, but will be walking into the theatre with low expectations.  Hopefully they come out with a better trailer....this trailer was not very inspiring...

text: I did some serious calculations and came to the conclusion that Independence Day 1 was prediction of 9/11 attacks. The movie was released on 3rd July 1996....The 9/11 attacks took places exactly 1896 days later. (ie., 1996 minus 100). In that movie, the first wireless contact (with aliens) was made on June 2nd....Marconi, the inventor of radio, made his first wireless transmission on June 2nd 1896. In the movie, the whole world unites setting aside all their differences.... In 1896, the whole world united setting aside all their differences to participate in the first Olympic Games. In the movie, a Black man (Will Smith, a US Navy pilot) captures the alien. Osama Bin Laden was killed by US Navy Seals under orders from US President Obama. In the movie, the alien space ship casts a shadow over the Twin Towers before proceeding to destroy a tall building....I can give another example. Pearl Harbor movie was released 115 days before 9/11 attacks. If you add 1896 to 115, you get 2011 the year Osama Bin Laden was killed.

text: -Chances are, anyone who is going to see this preview has already seen the movie but I had to put in my 2 cents. When I first heard that Will Smith declined coming back for this sequel I was disappointed and annoyed. Annoyed that he would skip the sequel to the movie that made him a star, but... now that I've seen this travesty, I understand why he said no. This is a generic, typical action flick of the early 2000s ala Armageddon and Pearl Harbor, Volcano, etc... Movies that are so bad they are laughable. I waited to see this at home because I did not want to waste money on a theater viewing. Now I have wasted more than money, I have wasted 90 minutes of my life. Yes, only 90 minutes because I cannot finish it. It is such a bad movie that I had to stop my viewing and write this to deal with the frustration of how bad a movie it truly is. This is bottom of the barrel stuff here, folks. Like, the slimy scum that bacteria lives in kind of stuff. You have been warned. -Lordy, I wanted to like this movie.

text: The iconic presences, for the greater part, are there and it's good to see them. Here's a movie that took me by surprise in staying true to the original's tone. I can appreciate as an age-contemporary of so many of the principal actors their contributions to Independence Day: Resurgence. So, as the successor to Independence Day this movie, glossier and more full-bodied, works for me. Judd Hirsch ("That's my David!") does not seem to have aged a day from the original and I am so glad to see him in a pivotal role with the edge of sly, comic relief in his character. William Fichtner, as he always does, elevates this film by his capable presence; see also Mr. Fichtner's performance as the thoughtful Delta operator in Black Hawk Down. One more example of a fine performance (of so many in this movie) is Maika Monroe as she seethes, convincingly, with emotion when her character's father, President Whitmore (Bill Pullman) goes forth to secure Earth for future generations against the hordes of marauding aliens.  I like this movie very much. New heroes, new thrills and a cast of thousands; what's not to like? Here, I can see Independence Day: Resurgence becoming a staple of HBO for another generation; it fits together so well with its predecessor. I am betting that time will tell in this film's favor.
